               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430612-name-1938" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430612-name-1938" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430612-name-1938" type="surname" value="STEWART"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430612-name-1938" type="given" value="ALEXANDER"></interp>ALEXANDER STEWART</persName>
                  </hi>. I am master of the <hi rend="italic">Mary</hi>, which laid off the Tower-stairs, in the Thames—the prisoner was an ordinary seaman on board—I wound up my watch on the 1st of June, about ten o'clock in the morning, and put it into my drawer in the cabin—I missed it next morning—I called the prisoner down, and said, "John, my watch is miss<lb></lb>ing; do you know anything about it?"—he said, "No"—I said, "You mean to say you know nothing about it?"—he said, "Yes, I am not a thief"—I left the vessel about three, and returned about ten in the evening—the prisoner was then gone—I did not see him again till the following Saturday about one, when he came on board, and I gave him in charge—this is my watch, it has my name on it—these are my seals and key, but the seals have been taken off—this ribbon is not on the watch, as it was before—I could take it off, and slip the seals off.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430612-name-1939" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430612-name-1939" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430612-name-1939" type="surname" value="MARTIN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430612-name-1939" type="given" value="ELIZA"></interp>ELIZA MARTIN</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the wife of Henry Martin, we keep a lodging-house in Unicorn-square. On Thursday evening the prisoner brought this watch and seals—he asked me if I would go and pledge the watch for him—he said it was his father's—I pledged it at Mr. Rosier's, in Long-lane—I gave the prisoner the duplicate—next morning he gave the ticket to my hus<lb></lb>band, and asked him to get some more money on it.</p>
